SIMPLE: flatter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flatter
<hw>Flat"ter</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, makes flat or
flattens.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Metal Working)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A flat-faced
fulling hammer.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A drawplate with a narrow,
rectangular orifice, for drawing flat strips, as watch springs,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flatter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flatter
<hw>Flat"ter</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flattered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Flattering</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[OE. <ets>flateren</ets>, cf. OD. <ets>flatteren</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>flattern</ets> to flutter, Icel. <ets>fla⟦edh⟧ra</ets> to fawn,
flatter: cf. F. <ets>flatter</ets>. Cf. <er>Flitter</er>,
<er>Flutter</er>, <er>Flattery</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To treat
with praise or blandishments; to gratify or attempt to gratify the
self-love or vanity of, esp. by artful and interested commendation or
attentions; to blandish; to cajole; to wheedle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When I tell him he hates flatterers,⟦br⟧
He says he does, being then most <qex>flattered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man that <qex>flattereth</qex> his neighbor, spreadeth a net for
his feet.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xxix. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Others he <qex>flattered</qex> by asking their advice.</q>
<rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To raise hopes in; to encourage or favorable, but
sometimes unfounded or deceitful, representations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To portray too favorably; to give a too favorable
idea of; <as>as, his portrait <ex>flatters</ex> him</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flatter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flatter
<hw>Flat"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To use flattery or insincere
praise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it may stand him more in stead to lie,⟦br⟧
Say and unsay, feign, <qex>flatter</qex>, or adjure.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flatterer</ent>⟦br⟧
